spanGrp.span: No me kakan kaka ne vōwal
The story is about a pigeon and a rat.
lēn qōn̄ ne vōwal n qono won gusōwō duruō e lama'i kēl rōs duruō
One day, there were a pigeon and a rat. The two didn't know each other.
So, how would the two become friends?
The pigeon, it was eating here and there.
di ne van ma di ne sag kal kēkē lēn qoro bē kal sag kēkēn woqen ge ne vōwal sa kēnē
It came here and it sat down high up above a river, on top of a tree right there.
Now sat down in order to sleep.
di ne sagsag 'i di ne rērē qēl suwē di ne 'ēn suwēn gusōwō ne kalu den ēn qoro nanara lēn lōlō qoro bē
As it was sitting there now, it glanced down and spotted a rat down there that had come out of a hole in a nanara (trunk) in the river.
'ei di ne tēk suwō mēn gusōwō
And so it said to the rat:
so 'ei nikē dada vie... sivie kēnē
'Hey, what are you up to here?'
gusōwō ne kalraka ne tēk sag mē die
The rat got up and said upwards to it:
sir e nik ga mi'ir kēkē no ga mi'ir qēl suweē
because you sleep up there and I sleep down here.
ba no ga mōrōs vesir nikē so
But I want to ask you:
nik ga 'ēn so qiri n wede luwo si ne gitag
Do you see whether there will be big rain tonight or not?'
qono ne kal raka ne vol die ne tēk mē die so
pigeon got up to answer him and said to him:
'o bulsal di me wede qiri ba di mas wede luwo m̄as
'Oh, friend, it will indeed rain tonight, but it shouldn't rain a lot.
'o ga gitok bulsal sir ēn ... nom vesir sir e nik ga mi'ir kēkē no ga mi'ir suwē
'Alright, friend, I asked because you sleep high up there, but I sleep down here.'
gusōwō ne kal raka ne kal ba'a kēl lēn lōlō qoro nanara
Then the rat got up and went back into the hole in the nanara (trunk)
as ōn 'i lēn qoro bē kōkō' 'i
that was lying in that dry creek.
When it got night, they slept.
wede dim wede dim mul mō'ōl
The rain, it rained, it got really heavy
da bē dim kalu ma dim 'ōn bē nanara 'a nē 'ō luō 'a lo van lēn vemimie
and so the water came out and carried the nanara trunk out to the sea going out (towards the deep sea).
ma'ava ma gōsuwō ne kal... ne ... ne lam̄a'a di ne 'ēn so
When it got morning the rat saw that
n ... n m̄ogi a dis mi'ir 'i lōlōgi a ... a tam balbal ne van rōw ne van sar
his house which he was sleeping in was seesawing, going back and forth.
dim lama'i raka so di man sal luō l... 'a vie lēn vemimie lēn naw
Then he realized that he had floated out somewhere into the open sea.
gōsuwō ne kal raka ne rōw lēn nanara luma sag k... kēkē' rōw? den ēn qorogi luma suwē ne rōw kal luma sag kēkē ne sag 'i
Then the rat got up and jumped on top of the nanara (trunk), jumped out of the hole at the bottom, jumped onto the upper side and sat there (for now).
ne sag 'i dōdōmia mugi ne van ne van ne vavan
And sat there. His thoughts went and went, on and on.
lēn masōgi di me dōm 'ar ēn sava ne vōwal
When he thought about one thing,
me le die me van kēl lēn lōlō vunuō
(that) will take him and (he) will go back onto the village.
As he was sitting and sitting (there)
di ne 'ēn rōw ma ne 'awokal ne 'awokal 'anēn nuō
he saw down in the deep sea, (s.th.)'s neck and head were suddenly visible, a turtle
'ei bulsal nikē dada sēvēe lēn bē nanara 'anē
'Hey, friend, what are you doing on this nanara trunk?'
'o bulsal gōsuwō ne tēk mē di
'Oh, friend' said the rat to him [turtle],
no nom 'ōg 'i nom mi'ir 'i lēn qoro nanara
'Me, I was staying (there) and I was sleeping in a hole in the nanara trunk.
ba nanara 'anē di ga ōn lēn qoro bē kōkō'
But this nanara (trunk), it was lying in a dry creek.
ban qono sam gal no ē so di mas wede luwo m̄as
And a pigeon lied to me saying that there wouldn't be heavy rain.
lēn qōn̄ da so nom kal ba'a lēn kēl lēn m̄ōk
Consequently, when I went back into my house at night,
lēn qōn̄ ēn wede dim wede
at night the rain, it rained
and the water took me, on and on,
kalu ma lēn veminie 'anē lēn lōlō naw 'anē
went out into the open sea, into the saltwater here.
'enei nos sag 'i 'anē no lama'i ros so no me van kal kēl sēvēe lēn n̄ērē'iē
Now I am sitting here and I don't know how I will get back to the shore.'
di ne tēk mē di so bulsal no no me birin̄ nikē 'amēn ga van 'ō nikē
he said to him: 'Friend, me, I will help you to bring you back.
nikē sag kēkē ma lēn kolok nok van 'ō nikē
Sit (down) here onto my back and I will take you.'
son gusōwō dim rōn̄rōn̄ 'i senē dim kal raka lēn lōlōgim malaklaka di ne rōw kēkē lēn nuō nuō ne van 'ō die
As the rat had heard this he got up, and his inside was glad. Then he jumped onto the turtle, and the turtle went with him [i.e. carried him].
nuōm ... n gō... gōsuwō dim r... r... rem kal rōw lēn kolo nuō nuō ne van van
When the rat had climbed onto the turtle's back, the turtle went.
duruk siw siw vavavavavan van din̄ man n̄erē'iē 'a vie di me mom di bēne
They swam and swam until they reached the shore where he was gonna put him.
nuō ne rem 'ō kal di lēn n̄ērē'iē
The turtle took him up to the shore,
van [UNCLEAR] sar lēn nōn gusuwō ne rōw sur den
went up to the beach. Then the rat jumped off down
ne virig sar lēn 'ōm̄... wōm̄ōm̄ō ne gilgil ēn qorogi 'amē tēk ēn tata mēn e ... 'amēn fga tēk ēn varian mēn e gōsuwō ... 'ee ... nuō
ran up into the bush and started to dig a hole? in order to say thank you to the rat?
'amēn ga tēk ēn tat... 'm varian mēn e nuō
in order to say thank you to the turtle. (?)
wo n 'an̄sar ne vōruō ne kalu wōl lēn n̄ērsigi wōlē
Then two people showed up at a point in <wōl>.
durum van ma van ma vavavavan ma din̄ ma duruk 'ēn mulen nuō
The two came closer and closer, and when they were close they spotted the turtle in <mul> .
One of them went <mul>wards and turned (it)
ne v... vil... wil 'a lan̄ ge'ew'i ne v..v..wil 'a lan̄ ēn nu.. nuō ē
turned ... the one turned the turtle onto its backside.
qē' duruk vrig kal kēl lēn lōlō vunu 'aram mēn e maranaga
After this the two rushed back into the village, reported (this) to the chief:
'Chief, a huge (piece of) meat (is) down at the sea.
We two have already turned (it) on its backside.'
sul dirēk 'ēqēl 'al marmar ēn nuō 'anē van 'ō kal ma
Then the people, they went down to the sea, tied up the turtle tightly and brought (it) up here.
dirēk van 'ō sar ... van 'ō sar lēn vunuō
They brought it up into the village.
lēn revrev dirēk qē'ēg 'ewen nev 'amēn ga ban̄ris ēn nuō 'anē
In the afternoon they started to make fire in the stone oven in order to bake the turtle.
dirēk 'ewe kal sag ēn nev won qono ne gav ma
When they were about to light the fire, the pigeon came flying.
n qono ne gav ma di ne tēk mēn e ... mēn e gōsuwō
The pigeon came flying and said to the rat:
gōsuwō 'amēn ga birin̄ nikē wo nik mē birin̄ ēn vuvulum a rekson 'ō nik ... 'ō nik ma den ēn naw 'ō ba ... 'ō ma nik lēn n̄ērē'iē
'Rat, for helping you, you will help your friend who brought you back to the shore.
I will conduct the following plan.
lēn masōgi dirēm van sar dirēm 'ewe kal ēn nev no no me laka wōlē
When they will have gone landwards and will have lit the fire, I, I will dance in <wōl>.
no me sor ēn 'erē m̄ēm̄ēlege rekson n sav... n..no... dir me 'ēn ga gitok mē no rekson qeseg
"qeseg" is a traditional body decoration made of reddish leaves worn on the back between the shoulders.
I will put on all kinds of things so that they see how good they are on me, like a 'qeseg'.
no me van no me 'ir lēn serege no me laka
I will go and stand on the village square and dance.
n sul dōl dir me van ma dir me ... dir me 'ēn nok laklaka
All the people, they will come and watch me dancing.
nikē nikē van nikē kur kirm̄ō san gaga a dirēm 'al ēn nuō bēne dan nuō ne 'ēqēl kēl ne mul kēl lēn vonogi
You, you go and bite the vine to pieces which they tied up the turtle with, and so the turtle will go down to the sea again, will return to his home.'
The rat said: 'Oh, friend, that's alright.'
som van din̄ man masōgi rekso 'amēn 'ewen nev dir'ōlm 'ewe kēl ... kal sag qēn nev
(Time) went on until it was time to light the fire. When they had lit the fire
n rōrōgi ne van ma so n ... n qono di me lak wōl gēn 'amēn sul dirēk 'ēn
the news came that a pigeon would dance in <wōl> so for the people to see.
son qono dim van ma 'ōn nōgin qeseg 'ir suw lēn serege 'anē laklaka
Then the pigeon came with his qeseg, landed on the village squared, danced.
laklaka n sul dōl 'e raga dōl len qan̄ris 'a dirēm 'e'ewe ... 'ewe kal 'ēn nev dir qē wōl lē..lēn serege dirēk 'en ēn qono ne laklaka
Danced, and the people, all the people who were busy with lighting the fire, they had not lit the fire yet, all of them were <wōl> on the square. And now they saw the pigeon dancing.
qono dim laka laka laka laka laka laka laka
While the pigeon, he was dancing and dancing
gōsuwō ne rōw sur rōw lu den ēn qorogi ne van
the rat jumped out of the hole and went
van din̄ man 'ekē a dirēm 'ewen nev bēne ne ... n qo.. 'ōon nuō ga 'ōn salma 'amēn dirēk ... dirēk 'ēv dirēk qan̄ris
until he reached the place where they had lit the fire. Oh, the turtle was lying ready so that they would cut it to pieces and bake it.
dim v... rōw kal sag lēn n n 'aqa nuwōm kur kur kuuōkur kur kirm̄ō qēn gaga
He jumped up onto the turtle's belly, bit and bit, bit the vine to pieces.
n nuō dim lan̄lan̄ ēn bēnēgi wēl wēl '.. wēl 'a vir kēl die
The turtle, he flailed his arms until he had turned himself around again.
di ne 'ēqēl van 'a'ag ēn mē'ēsala ne 'ēqēl
He went down to the sea, went down following the path,
van van vavavan ne van din̄ man n naw
went on and on, and then reached the saltwater.
dim van din̄ man naw di ne kal raka di ne wōswōs ēn naw
When he had come to the saltwater, he got up and smacked the saltwater.
qono sar lēn sērēge di ga rōn̄ 'i so nuō di wom van qē' di me lan̄ ēn naw vag'ōl qono ne qē' laklaka sar lēn sērēge
The pigeon up on the village square, it understood that when the turtle has gone he will smack the saltwater thrice, and the pigeon will stop dancing up on the village square.
so dim van din̄ rōw ēn naw dim lan̄ ēn naw vag'ōl n qono dim rōn̄ so n nuō di man din̄ lēn naw
So, when he arrived down at the sea he slapped the saltwater thrice and the pigeon, he realized that the turtle had reache the sea.
di ne kal raka di ne tēk mēn 'e raga sul so
He [pigeon] got up and said to the peopleː
wunva 'e raga sul ēn sava nom ... no me ... no me da 'aram mē kimi sin laklaka no me lak 'aram mē kimi di ... di vuva sa nē
'Probably, people, there is something I would like to express to you, or the dance I would like to convey a message to you through my dancing. That's it.
so lēn masōgi 'anē 'e raga dir'ōlm kal raka van kēl lēn 'ekē a rekso dirē me qan̄ris ēn nuō gore bene
At this point in time, the people got up and went back to the place where they would bake their turtle.
dirēk 'ēn vuva ēn gagas ōn 'i ne gitag ēn nuō bene
they only found the vines lying around there, (but) there was no turtle.
son n kakaka 'e sēvēen gōsuwō dim sal 'i lēn bē wōqē'enge
So that's the story (about) how the rat floated on the trunk of a tree
wo dim kēl ma lēn n̄ērē'iē
and how he got back to the shore.
a... 'esēvēen dim 'm...'m... m tēktēk lēn qono sin qono dim kaka mē die
How he talked to the pigeon, or how the pigeon talked to him.
wunvan kakaka di me qe'i wuva sa kēnē
Probably, the story, it is simply over right here.
